    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-08-28T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-08-28T14:00:00-05:00" n="276"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d276">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.011/8–2748: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        United States Political Adviser for Germany</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MRD1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murphy</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at Berlin</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d276fn1">The substance of this message was also sent by
                        Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DWH1">Draper</persName> to General
                            <persName corresp="#p_CGLD1">Clay</persName> as telegram W–88381, August
                        29, not printed.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-08-28T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 28, 1948—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1546. While we concur in Military Governors position expressed <gloss
                        target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 2117<note n="2" xml:id="d276fn2">Not
                        printed, but see footnote 1 to telegram 1543, August 27, to Berlin, <hi
                            rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> that Berlin representatives should not
                    vote, we would not object to Berlin attendance at Bonn meeting as we feel this
                    is question primarily for German decision. We note however that Brit and Fr <pb
                        facs="0451" n="417" xml:id="pg_417"/> will probably block this. Your tel
                        2173<note n="3" xml:id="d276fn3">Not printed; it reported that the British
                        Political Adviser had urged Berlin political leaders to give up their plans
                        to participate in the forthcoming Parliamentary Council. Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">Murphy</persName> foresaw a troublesome
                        situation if the Berlin leaders persisted in their intention and asked for
                        instructions from the Department (862.011/8–2748).</note> apparently crossed
                        <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 1543.<note n="4" xml:id="d276fn4">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> In the circumstances we should not
                    press matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
